In article <1992Jun15.214526.27797@wdl.loral.com>, mab@wdl39.wdl.loral.com (Mark A Biggar) writes:
> 
> Where did the idea come from that it took 2^47 excryptions to use the
> B&S machine attack?  It one takes one known plaintext and if the
> person your are attacking used some form of standard message header you
> don't even have to trick him, he is already using a known plaintext.

I think you're confusing the Biham and Shamir differential cryptanalysis
attack, which does indeed require 2^47 encryptions, with the Diffe and
Hellman exhaustive search using 1,000,000 special-purpose chips.
